From the output you shared, the pod is not pending because of memory or PVCs. The scheduler clearly tells you the reason.

Root cause

The event shows:

0/1 nodes are available:
Insufficient openshift.io/pci_sriov_net_bh0u_3
Insufficient cpu
Insufficient hugepages-1Gi

The first failure was:

Insufficient openshift.io/pci_sriov_net_bh0u_3

Your pod requests:

openshift.io/pci_sriov_net_bh0u_3: 1

But in the node capacity you pasted earlier, I only see:

openshift.io/pci_sriov_net_bh0u
openshift.io/pci_sriov_net_bh0u_1
openshift.io/pci_sriov_net_bh0u_2
openshift.io/pci_sriov_net_bh0u_2_1

I do NOT see:

openshift.io/pci_sriov_net_bh0u_3

So Kubernetes cannot allocate that SR-IOV resource.


---

Also check CPU and HugePages

Your pod requests:

CPU = 26 cores

HugePages = 8Gi


Node allocatable:

CPU = 106
HugePages = 18Gi

Already allocated:

CPU = 80%
HugePages = 16Gi

That means only approximately:

CPU free ≈ 21 cores

HugePages free = 2Gi


Your pod needs:

26 CPU

8Gi HugePages


So even if the SR-IOV VF existed, there still aren't enough CPU and hugepages available.


---

Verify the SR-IOV resource

Run:

oc describe node <node-name> | grep -A20 Allocatable

or

oc get node <node-name> -o json | jq '.status.allocatable'

See whether:

openshift.io/pci_sriov_net_bh0u_3

is present.


---

Check the SR-IOV NetworkNodeState

oc get networknodestate -n openshift-sriov-network-operator

Then:

oc describe networknodestate <node-name> -n openshift-sriov-network-operator

Verify that a VF pool for bh0u_3 has actually been created.


---

Check the NetworkAttachmentDefinition

Run:

oc get net-attach-def bscf-bh0u-3-nad -o yaml

Look for:

resourceName:

If it is:

resourceName: bh0u_3

then the node must advertise:

openshift.io/pci_sriov_net_bh0u_3

If it doesn't, the SR-IOV policy hasn't created that resource.


---

Most likely issues (in order)

1. ❌ openshift.io/pci_sriov_net_bh0u_3 resource is not advertised by the node.


2. ❌ Only 2Gi HugePages are free, but the pod needs 8Gi.


3. ❌ Only about 21 CPUs are free, but the pod requests 26 CPUs.



Please share the outputs of these commands:

oc get sriovnetworknodepolicy -A

oc get networknodestate -n openshift-sriov-network-operator

oc get net-attach-def bscf-bh0u-3-nad -o yaml

oc describe node <worker-node>

These will confirm whether the problem is the missing SR-IOV resource, insufficient CPU/hugepages, or all three.
